    "id": "script_stack_015",
    "name": "Supreme Verdict \u2014 uncounterable wrath",
    "description": "p1 casts Supreme Verdict ({1}{W}{W}{U}). p2 attempts to counter it with Counterspell, but Supreme Verdict cannot be countered (CR 101.2). p2's Counterspell fizzles on an illegal target and goes to graveyard without effect. All creatures are then destroyed. Tests the 'can't be countered' property.",
    "cr_sections_tested": [
      "601.2",
      "608.2",
      "702.113",
      "113.6",
      "608.2b"
    ],
    "corner_case_ref": null,
    "tags": [
      "board-wipe",
      "uncounterable",
      "supreme-verdict",
      "counterspell-fizzle",
      "cant-be-countered"
    ],
    "confidence": "medium",
    "review_status": "approved",
    "reviewed_by": "claude-sonnet-4-6",
    "review_date": "2026-02-23",
    "generation_notes": "Supreme Verdict oracle: 'This spell can't be countered. Destroy all creatures.' Cost {1}{W}{W}{U}. CR 702.113: 'can't be countered' means the spell isn't countered when resolving; Counterspell targets it but when Counterspell resolves, Supreme Verdict's 'can't be countered' property means the counter effect doesn't apply and the spell continues to resolve. Actually per CR 101.2: if a spell 'can't be countered,' instructions to counter it are simply ignored. The Counterspell spell still resolves (the cast was valid), but the effect is a no-op on Supreme Verdict. This is medium confidence due to the nuance of 'can't be countered' interaction.",
    "disputes": []
  },
